  "prompt": "How do calculate the gear ratio?",
  "response": "To calculate the gear ratio, follow these steps:\n\n1. For a single pair of gears:\n- Count the number of teeth on the driving gear (input gear)\n- Count the number of teeth on the driven gear (output gear)\n- Gear Ratio = Number of teeth on driven gear \u00f7 Number of teeth on driving gear\n\nExample:\n- Driving gear has 20 teeth\n- Driven gear has 40 teeth\n- Gear Ratio = 40/20 = 2:1\n\n2. For multiple gear stages:\n- Multiply the gear ratios of each stage\n- Total Gear Ratio = (Gear Ratio Stage 1) \u00d7 (Gear Ratio Stage 2) \u00d7 (Gear Ratio Stage 3)\n\n3. For planetary gears:\n- Use the formula: Gear Ratio = (1 + [Ring Gear Teeth / Sun Gear Teeth])\n\n4. Alternative calculation method:\n- Gear Ratio = Input Speed \u00f7 Output Speed\n- Or: Gear Ratio = Output Torque \u00f7 Input Torque\n\nThe gear ratio determines the relationship between rotational speed, torque, and direction of rotation between interconnected gears.",
